Notebook[{
Cell["Metric Algebra Tutorial", "Title",ExpressionUUID->"dab7d4ef-5002-417b-b691-fdfb7c5c4c9a"],

Cell["\<\
The metric algebra layer organises numerical invariants of the shortest-path \
metric: the metric interval, geodesic counts, the distance-multiplicity \
matrix, the test for distance matrices, and median vertices. These are the \
synthetic-to-analytic-to-algebraic bridge: distances on a graph become \
matrices that satisfy a tropical-idempotence relation, the matrix-form \
triangle inequality.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"81562983-413c-4207-97a6-2aa785779551"],

Cell["Setup", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"1db56bd7-92e6-4b92-9343-524114576cc2"],

Cell["Needs[\"WolframInstitute`SyntheticInfrageometry`\"]", "Code",ExpressionUUID->"c5145e4e-fded-40fd-94ff-e29a1cb019cf"],

Cell["The metric interval", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"e3692cbe-741d-4f73-8a9b-180aff2528de"],

Cell["\<\
The metric interval I(u, v) = { w : d(u, w) + d(w, v) == d(u, v) } is the \
union of all geodesics from u to v -- the master operation of the metric \
algebra layer.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"76d2d9ac-4c2f-4ebe-9e33-e22b64634bb3"],

Cell["MetricInterval[GridGraph[{3, 3}], 1, 9]", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"06060966-e2e5-49c3-9d73-a261506299e1"],

Cell["\<\
The interval contains every vertex on every shortest 1-9 path. On a tree the \
interval is exactly the unique geodesic vertex set; on a grid it is much \
wider.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"7db593a5-ebae-4ed6-a618-748847c349da"],

Cell["Geodesic counts", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"8bd500ab-ad93-472e-a873-cb5518e880af"],

Cell["\<\
GeodesicCount[g, u, v] returns the number of distinct geodesics from u to v. \
Computed in polynomial time as (A^d)[u, v] where A is the adjacency matrix \
and d = d(u, v).\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"72e89315-5ba9-4c27-af8f-533bb24d894b"],

Cell["GeodesicCount[GridGraph[{3, 3}], 1, 9]", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"a073ffe0-bc7b-44f1-9f1c-2675db823520"],

Cell["GeodesicCount[CycleGraph[6], 1, 4]", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"7eded275-81a4-447c-ac7a-622291721f96"],

Cell["\<\
Six geodesics on the grid (the lattice paths from one corner to the other) \
and two on the cycle (one for each side).\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"54ef3bf4-5f7e-4984-8dee-02d46dafab24"],

Cell["The distance-multiplicity matrix", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"bbf0258e-a967-467d-8da7-8bc6f4f26c9e"],

Cell["\<\
DistanceMultiplicityMatrix[g] returns {D, M} where D is the n x n distance \
matrix and M is the geodesic-count matrix.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"10abd041-8261-425a-8388-7b489d8b88d0"],

Cell["\<\
{distMat, mulMat} = DistanceMultiplicityMatrix[GridGraph[{3, 3}]]; \
MatrixForm[mulMat]\
\>", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"ca00c544-a634-4205-9254-8911e7e4b9fd"],

Cell["The matrix-form triangle inequality", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"58178a7b-599d-4932-9132-f60854f2baf1"],

Cell["\<\
DistanceMatrixQ[M] tests whether a matrix can be the distance matrix of some \
graph: square, symmetric, zero on the diagonal, non-negative entries, and \
tropical-idempotent (TropicalDot[M, M] === M, the matrix-form triangle \
inequality in the min-plus semiring).\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"52b0fa9d-3215-483a-a041-b69622a0f42d"],

Cell["DistanceMatrixQ[GraphDistanceMatrix[GridGraph[{3, 3}]]]", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"8a6317cf-3a78-4809-8b23-20f4d27e9e34"],

Cell["A bogus matrix that violates the triangle inequality:", "CodeText",ExpressionUUID->"a1278c4e-8951-4ea7-9774-755163d1136c"],

Cell["DistanceMatrixQ[{{0, 1, 5}, {1, 0, 1}, {5, 1, 0}}]", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"5dbe413d-f255-4e58-a956-ed89dda80716"],

Cell["The triangle inequality fails because 5 > 1 + 1.", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"9b5afa50-0791-4678-bcd1-a691b1741059"],

Cell["The bridge to TropicalOperations: A^k = D for k >= diameter", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"57d71c34-4cfe-4ed0-95ed-b1d717a61523"],

Cell["\<\
Tropical matrix powers of the cost-adjacency matrix converge to the distance \
matrix at the diameter step.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"f5127784-b8f5-42a5-8001-67f10e51878f"],

Cell["g = GridGraph[{3, 3}]", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"6901f250-f620-4fd0-bdb8-56f714d8107d"],

Cell["\<\
A = AdjacencyMatrix[g] /. {0 -> Infinity, 1 -> 1}; D = \
GraphDistanceMatrix[g]; TropicalMatrixPower[A, GraphDiameter[g]] == D\
\>", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"01aab451-b126-4b88-b7a6-d972ea19f16b"],

Cell["\<\
Past the diameter the iteration is stable -- additional iterations leave the \
matrix unchanged.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"0e3c8104-0799-495b-8318-efa9389aaea6"],

Cell["TropicalMatrixPower[A, GraphDiameter[g] + 5] == D", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"d4eca3c5-9da5-4a96-ad14-821faf4a88b6"],

Cell["Median vertices", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"be79a0e3-ba6f-4a95-9174-353f574657c6"],

Cell["\<\
MedianVertices[g, vs] returns the vertices minimising the sum of graph \
distances to the given vertex list. For a triple {a, b, c} this is the metric \
median(s); a graph is a median graph iff every triple has a unique median.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"31c58c02-cea8-42d1-8446-2c7467b2e9ec"],

Cell["MedianVertices[HypercubeGraph[3], {1, 4, 6}]", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"3e06db3a-9f5f-4be5-b145-454dd9dc7d30"],

Cell["\<\
Hypercubes are median graphs (the median is unique). The 6-cycle is not:\
\>", "CodeText",ExpressionUUID->"fc940362-b252-4dc3-a798-2037b9780d7f"],

Cell["MedianVertices[CycleGraph[6], {1, 3, 5}]", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"5a97569f-eebc-4c7e-9c25-f2f7d7d6531d"],

Cell["See also", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"1e65956d-1fee-4963-92de-3b06e2338d64"],

Cell["MetricAlgebraGuide -- categorical overview.", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"5421fa33-b681-4a38-9139-d7646bdec257"],

Cell["\<\
TropicalOperationsGuide -- the min-plus arithmetic underlying the matrix-form \
triangle inequality.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"5e2b5949-d317-48e2-ba9a-91096a5bbc4e"],

Cell["\<\
TropicalConvexityGuide -- median vertices feed into geodesic-convex-hull \
constructions.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"17e32e36-4285-473b-9f05-bc98625d8993"],

Cell["References", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"51a939cc-0ea0-417e-9a67-c8eb2fd3f8a5"],

Cell["\<\
Mulder, The Interval Function of a Graph, Mathematical Centre Tracts 132, \
Amsterdam 1980.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"5c7c0b30-158b-4331-a8ae-657cb2893eb9"],

Cell["\<\
Bandelt and Mulder, Distance-Hereditary Graphs, J. Combin. Theory Ser. B 41, \
182-208, 1986.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"e6d60af0-b1c1-479b-a7f0-afce22f603e1"],

Cell["\<\
Linial, Geodesic Geometry on Graphs, \
https://www.cs.huji.ac.il/~nati/PAPERS/ge_ge_gr.pdf\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"c257997d-34fa-46f3-b0a6-4a396b9de39c"]
},
